narratives.question_text: What are the strengths and weaknesses of this course and how could it be improved?
comments:
strengths: the content itself is pretty straightforward, the ULAs are GREAT so you always have easily accessible people to help you complete problem sets and study for exams. It is very possible to do well on exams, and the practice exams are often similar in difficulty. 

weaknesses: 1. I did not feel like my teacher explained the concepts very well and I ultimately did most of my learning in office hours with the ULAs. 2. Particularly for the final, I did not feel like the practice material reflected what the exam looked like. 3. class is so slow and doesn't actually prepare you for the problem sets. Spent all my time in office hours figuring them out, because I did not feel like class set me up to understand them or even know where to begin.

Strengths were the review sessions and class environment. Weakness were the teaching style and disorganization of the course. Hated the grading system of P-sets and exams as there was either too many marks for short questions or it was not transparent or consistent as to where I was gaining or losing marks.

The course could be improved
Strengths were in the office hours/ULA... I feel like I only re-learned topics from my past education and just strengthened that knowledge through p-sets. I wish I was more engaged overall.

narratives.question_text: Would you recommend this course to another student? Please explain.
comments: No, this was a very plain course, just do it if you need a prerequisite fulfilled.

If you need it for your major, definitely 110 and 111 over 112. 112 is really not necessary and 110 just has a better balance and course demand. Overall a pretty decent calculus course, but if you don't need it for your major there are probably better QR credits.
Only to fulfil your requirement, it was not very engaging.
Yes I would because it is a straightforward class
Yes if you need an easy QR, the 110/111 sequence is an easy way to get both credits
